<section id="what-are-exoplanets">
    <h2>What are Exoplanets?</h2>
    <p>Exoplanets, or extrasolar planets, are planets that exist outside our solar system. They orbit stars other than our Sun and can vary widely in size, composition, and distance from their stars.</p>
    <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/800x400?text=Exoplanet+Illustration+1" alt="Exoplanet Illustration 1">
    <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/800x400?text=Exoplanet+Illustration+2" alt="Exoplanet Illustration 2">
</section>

<section id="how-discovered">
    <h2>How are Exoplanets Discovered?</h2>
    <p>Scientists use various methods to detect exoplanets, including:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Transit Method:</strong> Observing the dimming of a star as a planet passes in front of it.</li>
        <li><strong>Radial Velocity:</strong> Measuring the star's wobble due to gravitational tugs from orbiting planets.</li>
        <li><strong>Direct Imaging:</strong> Taking pictures of planets directly by blocking the star's light.</li>
        <li><strong>Gravitational Microlensing:</strong> Observing the light from distant stars that gets bent by the gravity of a planet.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section id="interesting-exoplanets">
    <h2>Interesting Exoplanets</h2>
    <p>Here are some fascinating exoplanets that have been discovered:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Kepler-186f:</strong> An Earth-sized exoplanet in the habitable zone of its star.</li>
        <li><strong>HD 209458 b:</strong> The first exoplanet discovered to have an atmosphere.</li>
        <li><strong>Proxima Centauri b:</strong> The closest known exoplanet to Earth, potentially in the habitable zone.</li>
        <li><strong>TRAPPIST-1 System:</strong> A system with seven Earth-sized planets, three of which are in the habitable zone.</li>
        <li><strong>WASP-12b:</strong> An exoplanet that is so hot it has a molten atmosphere.</li>
    </ul>
    <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/800x400?text=Exoplanets+Gallery" alt="Gallery of Exoplanets">
</section>

<section id="planet-profiles">
    <h2>Exoplanet Profiles</h2>
    <div>
        <h3>Kepler-186f</h3>
        <p>Kepler-186f is notable for being the first Earth-sized planet discovered in the habitable zone of another star. It is about 500 light-years away and orbits a red dwarf star.</p>
        <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/400x200?text=Kepler-186f" alt="Kepler-186f">
    </div>
    <div>
        <h3>HD 209458 b</h3>
        <p>HD 209458 b was the first exoplanet discovered to have an atmosphere. It is located about 150 light-years away and is often referred to as "Osiris".</p>
        <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/400x200?text=HD+209458+b" alt="HD 209458 b">
    </div>
    <div>
        <h3>Proxima Centauri b</h3>
        <p>Proxima Centauri b is the closest known exoplanet to Earth and lies within the habitable zone of its star, Proxima Centauri.</p>
        <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/400x200?text=Proxima+Centauri+b" alt="Proxima Centauri b">
    </div>
</section>

